# Project Conventions

## Commands

```bash
build:     <build-command>
test:      <test-command>        # Prefer targeting a single file for speed
typecheck: <typecheck-command>
lint:      ruff check . && ruff format --check .
```

## Directory Layout

```
src/          # Application source code
tests/        # Test files mirroring src/ structure
docs/         # Architecture docs and ADRs
infra/        # Infrastructure-as-code (restricted — see AGENTS.md)
.cursor/      # Agent configuration (rules, plans, commands, skills, hooks)
```

## Dependency Rules

- Do **not** add new runtime dependencies without noting them in your task summary.
- Prefer existing utilities in `src/utils/` before pulling in a new library.
- Pin exact versions in lock files; never use `*` or `latest`.

## Library Documentation

Use Context7 when writing code that depends on an external library or framework.
Add `use context7` to your prompt, or ask directly:

```
use context7 to show me how to set up middleware in Express 5
use context7 with /vercel/next.js for app router file conventions
```

This fetches current, version-accurate docs rather than relying on training data.

## After Any Code Change

1. Run typecheck — zero errors required.
2. Run tests — all must pass.
3. Run lint — zero warnings required.
